{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/solving-non-linear-problems-with-genetic-algorithms-part-1-381702b0140e", "time": 1683007069.050849, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/solving-non-linear-problems-with-genetic-algorithms-part-1-381702b0140e/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Solving non-linear problems with genetic algorithms (Part 1) | by Pierre-Louis Bescond | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Solving non-linear problems with genetic algorithms (Part 1)", "description": "In this series of articles, discover how genetic algorithms (also called evolutionary algorithms) can help you solve non-linear problems!"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["Most machine learning use-cases aim at providing the best possible predictions, inferred from input features.", "But imagine that you would like to determine what is the best combination of features\u2019 values to reach a specific target.", "When the model you are using is non-linear and its corresponding function unknown (ex. Ensemble Trees), traditional optimization algorithms are useless.", "This is a typical use-case we face in the industry, which can be illustrated as follows:", "First, let\u2019s create a use-case where n features (X) lead to a numerical output (y):", "We create a non-linear model (here Random Forest) thanks to these historical values without any specific optimization work on hyper-parameters, cross-validation, etc.", "We take the opportunity of having this model being built to determine the features\u2019 importance:", "We will cover more advanced techniques in the next articles but the first and easiest way to find a combination of features\u2019 values which would lead to our target is to generate a large and randomized amount of potential solutions.", "The bigger the population is, the more likely we are to find one individual which would fit with our needs.", "Thus, for each feature, we create a uniform distribution of values, between the minimum and maximum observed of said-feature.", "For each row (individual) of the population, we can evaluate the model prediction (Y) and its corresponding distance from the target:", "It is now only a matter of selecting the best(s) individuals among this population:", "As you might have guessed, the larger the population is, the smaller the distance from the target will be for the best solution:", "This method, yet simple, might also require high computation power as the number of features and constraints increases.", "In the next articles, we will explore smartest ways to generate successive populations and reach our target.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Head of Data & Advanced Analytics @ Roquette | Winner of the 1st WorldWide Data Centric Deep Learning Contest | Data Science & Machine Learning Passionate!"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F381702b0140e&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fsolving-non-linear-problems-with-genetic-algorithms-part-1-381702b0140e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fsolving-non-linear-problems-with-genetic-algorithms-part-1-381702b0140e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav---------